:: AreaFocusedStrategy
<<set $step = 0>><<ShowInfo>><<set $day += 45>><<GenerateTimeSkipWorries 45>>
<<set _areaOutcome = random(1, 100)>>

<h3>The Area-Focused Approach</h3>
<div class="consequence-text">
	<p>You develop a routine: each morning, you take a single rideshare ($18-22) to a neighborhood where you know there are job opportunities. Once there, you plan your day around jobs within walking distance.</p>
	<p>It works well at first. You're saving money on transportation - only one rideshare each direction per day, around $40 total, instead of $60-80 if you were going to individual locations. Your tools are with you, you look professional, and you're not worried about police.</p>
	<p>You take painting jobs, repair work, small construction gigs - whatever's available within your chosen area each day. The work is steady enough.</p>
	<p>But after six weeks, you start noticing a problem.</p>
	<p>A client calls and asks if you can come paint their house across town. Good pay - $200 for a day's work. But it's too far from your usual area. You'd need a separate rideshare just for that job, eating into profits. You turn it down.</p>
	<p>A week later, another opportunity: emergency repair job, needs to be done today, client will pay well. But it's in a different neighborhood. You turn it down again.</p>
	<p>Then another. And another.</p>
	<p>You're saying "no" to jobs because they don't fit your transportation constraints. And in the informal economy, word gets around.</p>
</div>
<hr>
<<if _areaOutcome <= 50>>
	<<goto "AreaFocusedFail">>
<<else>>
	<<goto "AreaFocusedSuccess">>
<</if>>

:: AreaFocusedFail
<<set $step = 0>><<ShowInfo>><<set $day += 30>><<GenerateTimeSkipWorries 30>>

<h3>Diminishing Returns</h3>
<div class="consequence-text">
	<p>Two more months pass, and the problems compound.</p>
	<p>The job coordinators you work with start calling you less often. When you ask why, one of them is blunt: "You turn down too many jobs. I need people who are flexible, who can go where the work is. You're too limited."</p>
	<p>Another tells you: "I had clients asking for you specifically, but you kept saying no because of location. Now they're using other workers. Those other workers are getting the referrals you could have had."</p>
	<p>Your reputation as a reliable worker is being replaced by a reputation as someone who's inflexible. Too picky. Can't be counted on when a job is outside your preferred area.</p>
	<p>The irony stings: you limited yourself to save money on transportation, but now you're losing jobs - and income - because of those limitations.</p>
	<p>Job offers become less frequent. Some weeks you're only working three or four days instead of six. Your income drops. The money you saved on rideshares is offset by the money you're not earning from lost opportunities.</p>
	<p>You still make rent each month, but barely. There's no savings, no progress toward a better situation. You're stuck in the same position, and your business prospects are declining.</p>
</div>
<hr>
<div class="warning-box">
	<p style="margin:4px 0;color: orange;"><strong>Outcome:</strong> Your attempt to save money on transportation has cost you reputation and job opportunities. You're earning less now than when you started, and your prospects are getting worse.</p>
</div>

