:: AreaFocusedCarShare
<<set $step = 0>><<ShowInfo>>

<h3>Shared Ownership</h3>
<div class="consequence-text">
	<p>You reach out to your network from the shelter. Word spreads quickly - there's another family in almost exactly the same situation. They've been saving too, doing rideshare work, dreaming of a car.</p>
	<p>You meet them at a coffee shop. They're from El Salvador - a husband and wife with two young children. They're cautious at first, but as you talk, you realize you have a lot in common. Same struggles, same dreams, same determination.</p>
	<p>"We have $800 saved," the husband says. "If you have $800, we could buy a car together."</p>
	<p>You discuss the details: who drives when, how to split gas costs, what happens if someone damages it, how to handle insurance. It's complicated, but it's doable.</p>
	<p>Together, you find a 2008 Honda Civic for $1,600. It's old but reliable. You each pay $800. You split the insurance ($150) and registration ($100) evenly.</p>
	<p>When you drive it home for the first time - your day to use it - you feel not just freedom, but community. You're not doing this alone anymore.</p>
	<p>Your wife is nervous at first. "What if there are problems? What if we disagree?"</p>
	<p>"Then we'll work it out," you tell her. "That's what community is."</p>
</div>
<hr>
<div class="success-box">
	<p style="color: green;"><strong>Success:</strong> You co-own a car with another family. Your costs are cut in half, and you've built a strong community connection. You'll need to coordinate usage, but you have reliable transportation now.</p>
</div>

